<h1>MSc/PGDip Interactive Media in Society: Analysis and Writing Practice*</h1>

											
																
		
		
		



		
			<span class="h4_red">UCAS Code:</span> Apply direct to the University<br />	
		
			<span class="h4_red">Duration:</span> One year full time; Two years part time<br />	
		
			<span class="h4_red">Number of Places:</span> 15<br />	
<br />
		
			<a href="#Intro">Introduction</a><br />	
		
			<a href="#Themes">Core Themes</a><br />	
		
			<a href="#Career">Career Opportunities</a><br />	
		
			
			
			
			
			
			
			
			
			
			
			
			
			
					
			
			
			
					
			<a href="#Entry">Entry Routes</a><br />	
		
		
<br />		

		
		
		
			
		

		
			
			
		

		
		
<br/>


			<h3 id="Intro">Introduction</h3><b>Key Features </b><br />â¢	Conceptual examination of interactive media technology systems and cultural narratives<br />â¢	Practical sessions dedicated to the development of small projects and technical writing skills <br />â¢	Develops an understanding of the complexity of contemporary culture <br /><br /><b>About this course</b><br />The profusion and multiplication of various modes of interactive art forms and factual communication has resulted in the need for professionals who are able to critically evaluate and write for these new and exciting interactive digital formats.<br /> <br />This postgraduate degree seeks to help you to integrate sociological analysis into writing practice in the field of Interactive Media. It places the world of interactive media in its social and historical context whilst also providing you with an industry-informed, practice-based element. The aim is to develop your individual career and personal aspirations through encouraging critical analysis and innovative practice. It therefore offers you the opportunity to critically review the potential of current and emerging technologies in contemporary interactive media, bringing together perspectives from Sociology and Computer Arts.<br /><br />Students undertaking this course have the option of exiting at Postgraduate Certificate, Postgraduate Diploma or Masters level. To attain the Postgraduate Diploma students will be required to complete all generic and subject specific core modules including the submission of a substantive research proposal. Attainment of the Masters qualification will be project focused with the submission of a research thesis.<br /><br /><b>*At the current time, this programme is still under development and is therefore subject to change and final approval.</b><br /><br/><br/>	
		
		

			<h3 id="Themes">Core Themes</h3><b>What you Study</b><br />Applied research methods; research dissertation; philosophical and ethical issues of social & health sciences; socio-historical analysis of interactive technology; writing for emergent media; independent learning module; narrative media forms; media, discourse & power.<br /><br /><b>How you learn </b><br />The programme has been designed with a range of learning experiences to develop your skills including lectures, seminars, master classes, workshop/studio based sessions, and  project-focused work. A key aspect of this programme is the opportunity to undertake a âconsultancyâ approach in terms of critical analysis of a topic and the production of an interactive media text. <br /><br /><b>How you are assessed</b><br />Your academic performance will be assessed through a range of methods designed to develop your critical reasoning and practical skills in this area, including essays, practical projects, portfolio projects, and individual and group presentations.  Each of these methods of assessment will give you different forms of feedback in order to help you develop your skills and progress through the programme.<br /><br /><br />	
		
		
		

			<h3 id="Career">Career Opportunities:</h3>The abundance of multimedia presentation and performance in the arts, and the telescoping of work opportunities in the new media sector have led to the need for graduates who can at one and the same time critically analyse and evaluate these areas as well as write various media texts. The careers that you may pursue following-on from the degree include:<br />â¢	Cultural & Media Researchers<br />â¢	Scriptwriters<br />â¢	Directors<br />â¢	Freelance Media Design Advisers<br /><br />	

		
